# Pattern: native OIDC — apps you build yourself

For apps that need to know *who* the user is and *which role* they hold:
the app becomes a full OIDC client of the central ZITADEL. It gets real
ID/access tokens, role claims, refresh tokens and clean logout —
fine-grained authorization per resource.

For third-party apps that cannot do their own auth, use
`patterns/app-forwardauth/` instead.

## 1. OIDC client (identity as code)

Add a file `tofu/zitadel/<app>.tf` — the client lives in the project of the
association the app belongs to (role claims of that project end up in the
tokens):

```hcl
resource "zitadel_application_oidc" "myapp_web" {
  org_id     = module.community.org_id
  project_id = module.community.project_ids["sports-club"]

  name             = "myapp-web"
  app_type         = "OIDC_APP_TYPE_WEB"
  response_types   = ["OIDC_RESPONSE_TYPE_CODE"]
  grant_types      = ["OIDC_GRANT_TYPE_AUTHORIZATION_CODE", "OIDC_GRANT_TYPE_REFRESH_TOKEN"]
  auth_method_type = "OIDC_AUTH_METHOD_TYPE_BASIC"

  redirect_uris             = ["https://myapp.{{ domain }}/auth/callback"]
  post_logout_redirect_uris = ["https://myapp.{{ domain }}/"]

  access_token_type           = "OIDC_TOKEN_TYPE_BEARER"
  access_token_role_assertion = true
  id_token_role_assertion     = true
  id_token_userinfo_assertion = true
}

output "myapp_oidc_client_id" {
  value     = zitadel_application_oidc.myapp_web.client_id
  sensitive = true
}

output "myapp_oidc_client_secret" {
  value     = zitadel_application_oidc.myapp_web.client_secret
  sensitive = true
}
```

`tofu apply`, then wire the credentials into the app via a SealedSecret:

```bash
cd tofu/zitadel
CLIENT_ID=$(tofu output -raw myapp_oidc_client_id)
CLIENT_SECRET=$(tofu output -raw myapp_oidc_client_secret)
cd ../..
kubectl create secret generic myapp-oidc -n myapp \
  --from-literal=OIDC_ISSUER="https://id.{{ domain }}" \
  --from-literal=OIDC_CLIENT_ID="$CLIENT_ID" \
  --from-literal=OIDC_CLIENT_SECRET="$CLIENT_SECRET" \
  --dry-run=client -o yaml \
  | kubeseal --cert sealed-secrets-public-key.pem -o yaml \
  > /tmp/myapp-sealed-oidc.yaml
```

Commit the SealedSecret where the app's manifests live (its own repo on the
blessed path).

## 2. Register the app

```bash
./scripts/new-app.sh myapp --repo https://github.com/{{ github_owner }}/myapp
```

The app repo owns `deploy/overlays/production` (deployment, service,
ingress with `cert-manager.io/cluster-issuer: acme`, the sealed secret).
Flux pulls it directly; rollout = push to `main`.

## 3. Authorize on role claims

With `project_role_assertion = true` the user's roles in the project arrive
as a claim:

```json
"urn:zitadel:iam:org:project:roles": { "board": { "...": "..." } }
```

The app checks the claim — e.g. `board` may edit, `member` may read.
Rich domain data (membership fees, join dates) does NOT belong in ZITADEL:
keep it in the app's database, keyed by the token's `sub` (ZITADEL = IdP,
not CRM — hard invariant).
